3":"1253","1272":"1272","1260":"1260","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1205":"1205","1259":"1259","1313":"1313","1225":"1225","1254":"1254","about 1225":"about 1225","about 1253":"1253","Walworth, Durham, England":"Walworth, Durham, England","South Kelsey, Lincolnshire, England":"South Kelsey, Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hansard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): of Norman origin, from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Ansard</i> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>; from ancient Germanic <i>ans-</i> ‘(pagan) god’ + <i>ward</i> ‘guard, protector’ or <i>hard-</i> ‘brave, hardy’."],"variants":[{"name":"Hazard","meanings":["English: Anglo-Norman French variant of   Hansard  .","English and French: nickname from Old French, Middle English <i>hasard</i>, <i>hazard</i> ‘game of dice’, perhaps given to a player at hazard, i.e. a gambler, trickster, or rascal. The word probably derives from Arabic <i>az-zahr</i>, from <i>az</i>, assimilated form of the definite article <i>al</i>, + <i>zahr</i> ‘die’. It appears to have been picked up in the Holy Land and brought back to Europe by Provençal crusaders.","English: possibly in some instances of Flemish origin, a nickname from Middle Dutch <i>hasart</i> ‘hare’."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"his